{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"714e82af-8651-4733-82cd-1404792b4d16","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting and filling disk.\n- Copy the file out with `kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"16005243-a8a1-4fea-a8d3-f709f53dc402","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":373,"requestId":"67C3:1EAD:48FB7ED:4FBEA0F:69FD3C78"},"id":"b4efa5e3-e6e2-45cd-ab3b-558f0259b7ad","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:29:37.868Z","parentId":"151956ef-de3a-48b9-9f36-35fe0f801e26"}
